Yes — with these new photos, I’d make only a few targeted changes in the group_vars_defaults role.

The main goal now is: stop treating workstation_defaults.yml as the bootstrap-generated file and make the role safe/idempotent when writing to:

collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all/aerolit_bootstrap_generated.yml

1. Fix defaults/main.yml

Your current defaults still point at workstation_defaults.yml, have hardcoded sample NFS values enabled by default, and still reference epel_is_approved.

Update these sections.

Replace this target file default

Current:

group_vars_defaults_file: "{{ playbook_dir }}/../ansible/group_vars/all/workstation_defaults.yml"

Use:

group_vars_defaults_file: "{{ playbook_dir }}/group_vars/all/aerolit_bootstrap_generated.yml"

Change NFS defaults to safe empty defaults

Current default behavior is risky because it has NFS enabled and sample values:

group_vars_defaults_manage_nfs_mount_defaults: true
group_vars_defaults_nfs_path_for_ansible: /home/unix/sysadmin
group_vars_defaults_nfs_mounts:
  - path: /home/unix/sysadmin
    mode: "0755"
    owner: root
    group: root
    src: "192.168.98.141:/srv/aerolit-bundle"

Change that to:

group_vars_defaults_manage_nfs_mount_defaults: false
group_vars_defaults_nfs_cleanup_legacy_keys: true
group_vars_defaults_nfs_marker: "# {mark} MANAGED AEROLIT NFS BUNDLE"
group_vars_defaults_nfs_path_for_ansible: ""
group_vars_defaults_nfs_mounts: []

This makes the role safe by default. bootstrap_controller.sh should be the thing passing the real NFS values.

Replace old EPEL example

